The victory of right-wing populists in Austria, they have a total of 29%
According to the first preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday brought about a noticeable weakening of the two parties of the Grand Coalition so far and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current President Wilhelm Molterer has been seriously shaken, has suffered a particularly strong loss.
On the other hand, the President of the Association for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the provincial magistrate of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, is preparing a winning return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the country's strongest party remains the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) with 29.8 percent of the votes, but it lost 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last 2006 elections.
The ÖVP was even worse, which loses nearly nine percent of the votes by 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both major parties in Austria's post-war history, and in particular the result is literally disastrous for the People's Party that brought about the early elections.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP coalition left, the People's Party had a significant advantage over the SPÖ, according to opinion polls.
However, the voters apparently punished him for letting the government fail.
The first reactions to the results have been speculation about the possible resignation of party president Wilhelm Molterer and current vice chancellor.
The observers believe that this will take place on Monday at the extraordinary meeting of the party presidency.
This development would probably facilitate an increasingly likely way out of the election result, i.e. the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP Grand Coalition.
In view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Austrian Freedom Party (FPÖ) had previously won 18 percent of the votes and the BZÖ 11 percent of the votes - however, the Social Democrats expressed their fear of the recurrence of 1999 when the People's Party agreed to a joint government with the populists (the FPÖ was still united in 2005, which even triggered sanctions from the BZÖ), which even triggered the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is willing to cooperate with any party and I assume that he can return to Vienna in national politics, obviously expects this solution.
The Green Party also entered Parliament, which, however, slightly lost its popularity and fell from the third place to the fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties exceeded the four percent limit and did not reach Parliament.
