Organizers are registering more and more bookings.
A good winter is coming for German tour operators.
According to one study, the traffic of road bookings for the coming months increased significantly compared to the previous year - by more than 30 percent for the winter season.
Despite the weak economic outlook, the German travel mood did not slow down, according to the study.
For winter season bookings, travel agencies recorded a 31 percent increase in traffic compared to the previous year, the German Travel Association (DRV) said on Monday in Berlin.
According to the GfK market research institute, the number of bookings for the autumn months is already higher.
Travel agents’ turnover in October was around 11 percent higher than in October 2007, DRV said.
These results are based on data from GfK, which evaluates the monthly booking data of 1,200 German travel agencies and then extrapolates it to the entire market.
The Institute took into account trips booked until the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak dollar exchange rate, travel to the US is particularly sought-after, the DRV said.
Here, the volume of reservations increased by about one third.
The Germans are also particularly popular destinations in Spain, Turkey and Greece, as well as in domestic landscapes.
“Organized travel is the most sought after,” said Klaus Laepple, president of DRV.
Due to rising energy and food costs, the costs for organized trips are "more calculable for passengers than for individually organized journeys."
Among other things, passengers can save money with pre-booking discounts or all-inclusive offers, Laepple added.
The booking rate for the summer months was also very good, so traffic growth will be recorded again compared to the previous year, although according to another study, fewer German tourists have undertaken a trip compared to the previous year.
