Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the east side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial effort.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neorenaissance style.
At least that's what the guidebooks say.
The building surrounds the end of the platforms with a tower at each front corner, and it looks like some kind of German rural town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building's a little shaky.
However, looking at the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious what a large undertaking this was the westernmost gate.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the "late future" of conquests, wanted to achieve its ambitions to occupy the Middle East with the help of this railway from Damascus to Baghdad to today's Saudi Arabia.
The German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha Station was no better.
In 1917, an ammunition train exploded and destroyed the well-developed roof of the building.
According to Turkish sources, there was a sabotage operation.
Since then, it has slowly collapsed, and history has gone far beyond it.
At the same time, today, as the gateway to Anatolia and the entire Eastern region, it serves, at least symbolically, as the expanding diplomatic horizon of Turkey.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has developed a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, Hamas and Fatah Palestinian groups, Iraq, Iran and, of course, the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded the night train to Ankara, the Turkish capital, to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, the Turkish Member of Parliament, Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours, which gave the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is intended as a symbol of the new secular state, which turns its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with known Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This caused some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern, stone-and-steel building specifically designed for this purpose - which is located in a developing suburban district between semi-finished shopping malls and cafés. In the latter, middle-leaders in suits - both men and women - meet to make a deal early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have been a right-wing politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy goal is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has upset order,” he said.
Turkey is isolated from its hinterland.
Today, he had to turn east and west at the same time.
He couldn't choose between the two.
It had to be opened in both directions.
"But is it possible that sooner or later he will have to choose?" I asked.
"Turkey never wanted to be at a crossroads."
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to almost mechanically repeated: Turkey’s relations with not only the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the countries surrounding the Black Sea are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as Turkey itself.
It is as if they want to convey the message that, figuratively speaking, with Turkey, the whole of Europe can reach Asia and the Middle East on those easterly railway lines.
When I was back at the Hydarpasha station, after another night, mostly awake, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conura, the two German gentlemen who watched the recovery of this fancy structure 100 years ago.
How they would have been surprised to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in Turkey's hands.
And as I waited in the harbor for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was once called "the sick man of Europe."
At that time, at least there was no question of which continent should claim this exciting country.
Memorable Life Paths: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: Since 1962, as musical director of Guildford, Vernon "Tod" Handley led the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
According to his musical plans for the part of the city, the following year he founded his wonderful youth choir, Proteus.
In principle, only those under the age of 21 could have been included in the choir, but when Proteus sang its finale in 1979 - many of us were already in our late 20s - we simply refused to part with the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the name of the mythological shape-shifter) was in line with the choir's determination and ability to cope with any sheet music that was put in front of it - whether it was madrigal or a Messiaen piece; without accompaniment or with orchestral accompaniment.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often amazing and always exciting, and we owe it to the man whose inspiration our enthusiasm for music has remained unchanged over the years.
How often did Tod tell us, "Let the music speak for itself."
He always said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the sheet music.
So sing it!"
His conductor technique was always completely understandable and accurate, but never dictatorial or exaggerating.
Whatever the standard of music was, he always raised it.
John Frayn Turner wrote:
If there was ever a conductor who should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I got to know him well during the two decades during which he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
In the last forty or so years, I have written reviews of more than 100 concerts, but it has never disappointed me, and it has often inspired me.
Tod Handley had greatness and modesty together, which is very rare.
He hated the conductors who, in his words, simply "walked with one or two well-known battlehorses all over the world."
Many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
