The "Bee Car" Avoiding Collision
For the development of accident-prevention technologies, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, specifically the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company designed a robot that imitates the flight of bees to avoid accidents.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in the development of crash prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technology Center, in collaboration with the renowned University of Tokyo’s Advanced Science and Technology Research Center, have built this small robot in Japan.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Director of Technology PR and Research and Development, defines the BR23C as a further extension of Nissan’s four-tier safety shield.
The robot enhances the ability of the company's products to avoid collisions.
During flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to Nissan's safety cover.
More important, however, is the role of the complex eye of the uterus, with which it can see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the complex eye, engineers designed a so-called laser range finder.
In front of the BR23C, the instrument identifies obstacles within a distance of up to 2 metres, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an action to avoid collision.
"As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot, imitating the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid collision.
The main difference between the system and the instruments currently available is that in this case the avoidance maneuver takes place completely automatically.
If that were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
In a way other than bees, the bypass maneuver cannot be directed upwards or downwards, nor can it move diagonally, only in two dimensions, and only in the direction of the turnability of the wheels, i.e. not in an infinite direction and manner, as in the case of bees.
That's why Nissan used a rotation function in addition to acceleration and deceleration in the robot to avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process and respond to data every few seconds.
There is no need for data storage or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can operate without interruption with only a few dozen KB memory.
This may sound surprising, but it's not gigabytes, but we're not even talking about megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which Nissan estimates will enter series production cars within ten years.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system may be an additional application to get the driver to the final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
