Morgan Stanley to open up capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced that it will provide a stake in Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG). The largest Japanese bank will pay $9 billion for 21% of the company's capital after Morgan Stanley's stock price fell sharply on the stock exchange.
A week after the preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks said that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley's ordinary shares at a unit price of $25.25, i.e. a total of $3 billion.
The accepted price is more than 19% below the book value of the securities on 31 August.
MUFG invests an additional $6 billion in the purchase of convertible securities, which provide it with a 10% return and a conversion rate of $31.25.
According to Morgan Stanley, the global transaction is based on an average exchange rate of $29, which is 28% higher than the current exchange rate.
However, Morgan Stanley's share price fell by 6.79% around 17:00 in Greenwich Mean Time, closing at $23.77.
“This strategic alliance provides Morgan Stanley with a great opportunity to accelerate its transformation into a banking holding company,” explains John Mack, CEO of the U.S. Group.
Morgan Stanley approved the new status last week, which allows it to diversify its activities, while at the same time being under the control of the Federal Reserve.
The agreement with MUFG reaffirms that the current financial crisis requires even more caution from the corporate giants listed on Wall Street.
On Monday, Morgan announced that it would sell 20% of its shares to the Japanese company for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, we thought that the share would consist entirely of ordinary shares,” said Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG in Tokyo.
However, due to the current market and economic situation, we wanted to minimise and prevent possible risks."
In terms of weighted average prices, MUFG pays 7% more than book value for Morgan Stanley shares.
As a result of the transaction, the return per share will be reduced by about 20%.
Under the agreement, MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into ordinary shares after one year if the latter's trading price exceeds the exchange rate by more than 50% over a specified period, i.e. it rises to approximately $47.
Morgan Stanley thus ensures that you can use funds from MUFG to take advantage of your investment opportunities, improve your balance sheet and increase your liquid resources.
However, the spokesperson of the group did not want to give accurate information about the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s partnership, Morgan Stanley is expected to increase its Tier I solvency rate by about 15%, making it one of the best in its own sector.
Morgan said that its balance sheet has improved "definitely" since the end of August.
The past few weeks have been a great ordeal for the group, as the price of its shares has fallen by half, while the cost of its non-payment risk insurance has skyrocketed.
This cost was reduced on Monday, but remained at a high level of around 12%.
Of the big investment banks, only one "survivor" remained after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch. This is Goldman Sachs, which announced last week that it had made $15 billion: part of it came from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett's group of companies.
Statement by Rafael Correa on Monday, Quito
Rebuilding the Republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is the joint plan of Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
Following the example of his fellow presidents and friends, Correa explained his ideas on the new constitution on Sunday.
His mission was successful, as 64% of the voters voted yes in the referendum according to the official results, which applied to 80% of the votes.
According to this, 28% of the population voted no, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% were cast unfilled.
The adoption of the draft constitution required 50% + 1 vote.
On Sunday, two polls at the polling station exits and a count by a non-governmental organization proved the huge superiority of "yes" votes by 63% and 70% respectively.
Rafael Correa, meanwhile, spoke of the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday night.
"The Constitution was an overwhelming victory," he said, thanking Ecuadorians at his governor's headquarters in Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez, Morales and Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.
According to the report of the Organization of American States (OAS), the vote took place in a calm atmosphere. Its main theme was a 444-point text that summarized the principles of "new socialism" defended by the President.
The proposed constitution places state power at the service of the economy, maintaining the right of the state to "plan development" for a country that basically lives on oil extraction by foreign companies and foreign exchange sent by emigrants.
The draft Constitution of Correa, elected in 2006, also strengthens the power of the Head of State, who can obtain a mandate for up to two consecutive periods and is entitled to disband the Parliament.
Correa has already announced that she intends to take advantage of this opportunity and will compete again for the mandate of Head of State in February 2009.
The president has already begun to introduce this in his country, which has 13.9 million inhabitants, and half of the population lives below the living standard.
Finally, the Constitution prohibits the presence of foreign troops in the country, which could put an end to Quito's and Washington's agreement to use the Ecuadorian facility as a base for US drug control measures.
19 hostages freed in Chad
Egyptian commandos raided the kidnappers who took 11 tourists and their eight escorts hostage ten days ago.
The hostages are now in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and eight Egyptian escorts were detained in the desert for ten days, from which they were transported unharmed to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
The hostages were freed by an Egyptian commando in Chad during the morning.
Apparently in good condition, they arrived by plane at the al-Maza military base around 4:30 p.m., which is directly connected to Cairo International Airport.
The hostages were forbidden to speak to the press and were immediately transferred to a hospital in Maadi, a suburb of Cairo, where they were examined.
The hostages are "healthy" and the kidnappers were "not paid a ransom," Egyptian tourism minister Zoheir Garanna said at the airport.
The hostages were captured on 19 September at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border regions of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they took part in an SUV safari.
The group included 11 tourists (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman) and eight Egyptians: two tour guides, four drivers, one border guard and the director of the Aegyptous travel agency organizing the safari.
According to an Egyptian security chief, a special commando of 30 members arrived on two helicopters at the scene, where the hostage takers were ambushed just before dawn.
"There was a firefight between the troops. Half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fled," said the leader who asked for his name to be kept quiet.
He also said that a total of 150 special forces were sent from the Egyptian Lightning Brigade to Sudan, where German and Italian commandos were added.
The Italian diplomatic leader Franco Frattini, who is currently in Belgrade, stressed the role of secret agents and special Italian action groups.
“We have to admit that we could not have achieved this without the professional and effective intervention of our Secret Service personnel and task forces,” he said.
He also denied paying a ransom for the hostages.
On the previous day, the Sudanese army announced that an SUV was intercepted while patrolling, on which the kidnappers traveled. Six of them were killed (including the Chadian leader) and two were arrested.
The army claimed that the hostage takers were associated with a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which was immediately refuted by the organization concerned.
Lettres - The "Silent Majority" of Culture
At the heart of the news and the ongoing election campaign is the debate on the financing of culture.
We should be happy about that.
But a part of our cultural life is still forgotten.
Who will raise their voice to highlight the ridiculous amounts of money being used to manage small museums, archives, archaeological excavations, and national historical sites on the brink of starvation?
What politician dares to remind the federal government that he does not care about his monuments and buildings that are part of his cultural heritage?
Or that there are no laws in Quebec or Canada that effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government spent three and a half million euros on the restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley alone?
The Constitution of our American neighbors states that the protection of cultural heritage is part of American culture, and this heritage must be protected in a coordinated manner by all citizens, all elected representatives and all government bodies.
Within the framework of the Federation des sociétés d'histoire du Quebec, more than 40,000 volunteers from 211 societies dealing with history, cultural heritage, archives and genealogy work to research history and preserve a large number of private archives and archaeological artifacts with a minimum budget.
Often these organizations defend our heritage tooth and nail and protest with the last force of drowning when real estate developers and decision-makers direct their bulldozers to our old buildings and forgotten cemeteries.
When will someone stand up for the protection of historical and cultural heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help with partial nationalisation at the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortison, the first European to be in trouble due to the spillover effect of the US credit market crisis: the three countries support the money and insurance institution with a total of EUR 11.2 billion.
The Belgian, Luxembourg and Netherlands governments agreed on the matter at the highest level at the end of the week, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission's Competition Commissioner.
In the euro area, Fortis Bank is the first major crisis in the international financial market crisis in waves for more than a year, and decisions on the bank can therefore be regarded as a precedent in some respects.
According to the decision made on Sunday night, nearly half (49%) of the bank's assets will be acquired by all three states.
The bank will certainly sell some of its interests, in particular the activities purchased last year from Dutch ABN Amro, mainly insurance companies.
Fortis shares started to fall sharply last week, and in the second half of the week there were serious crisis phenomena at the institute.
However, analysts agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is too large to be allowed to go bankrupt.
The company's records fell to a 14-year low on Friday alone.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
In terms of current stock prices, the total market capitalisation of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the CEOs this is not realistic.
The company blamed overseas market uncertainties related to the adoption of the $700 billion U.S. package plan for the fall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers rose slightly.
On Friday, a new CEO, Filip Dierckx, was appointed to lead the bank.
The financial institution has also been looking for private buyers, but no one has come forward with a meaningful offer.
The Belgian government has already indicated that investors do not have to worry about losing their money.
So far, there's been no panic among the bank's clients, no storming of the branches.
In Hungary Fortis has an independent branch and has also acquired leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with the applicant based on people’s drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a data protection program that always links the use of prescribing data to the consent of the person concerned.
This has to be in independent hands, otherwise we'll leave the chicken coop to the fox," said Richard Dick, the developer of the drug prescription program.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the amount due in the event of damage dependent on the health status of the applicant client, and if they consider the risk to be too high, they do not take out insurance with it.
In the past, the person was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the knowledge of the results of the investigation.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: from pharmacies, based on the customer's identification number, he easily obtains what drugs he has purchased in the last year and a half, and from this the program itself concludes what disease he suffers and what his health status is.
For example, if you regularly take a high dose of cholesterol lowering, it suggests that you have virtually unmanageable levels of fat in your blood, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the programme in circulation, some of which also define a risk multiplier, so the insurance company has little to do other than paperwork, although there are small difficulties.
The disadvantages include that some medicines can be used for several purposes, for example, some compounds can be used against migraines or heat waves, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is a significant risk-enhancing factor for business insurers, the former not.
Separate companies were formed to retrieve and process the data, and before they obtain the necessary information from pharmacies, they ask the patient’s consent.
They are now obliged to do so by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their failure so far.
Recently, some companies have also processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to drug consumption data, so that they can provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and at the same time it will be increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a separate health data protection law, but it applies only to health care providers and insurers.
Congress has before it a bill that gives the authorities control over businesses that specialize in data provision.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough: he has therefore improved his programme, which would make the transfer of data conditional on the explicit consent of the data subject.
Another question is that the person concerned can hardly refuse to consent, otherwise the insurers will not enter into a contract with him.
So the hens are somewhat dependent on the fox's benevolence.
Global Marseilles menu
India and the European Union to double trade
As the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, the agenda of the ninth summit was dominated by this issue, alongside the other, largely global, problems.
Today, there will also be a French-Indian summit, where nuclear energy cooperation will be the main focus.
The European Union acknowledges that India is an emerging democratic power that should have a greater say in international affairs, but the Member States have not yet managed to reach a common understanding whether to support New Delhi's permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This issue was not even raised at the ninth summit held in Marseille yesterday.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as President-in-Office of the European Union, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and High Representative Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade in five years, i.e. to EUR 100 billion.
Given that trade between 2000 and 2007 has risen from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious goal.
In this spirit, the twenty-six bilateral civil aviation agreements with India have been legally consolidated, i.e. air traffic may soar in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the fact that while the EU is India's number one trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth in the EU's list of partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, as well as terrorism - the latter was condemned on both sides in all its forms and urged the convening of a UN conference.
They also called for the end of the Doha trade round, although both of them are a large part of the failure so far.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, which means that it wants to reduce emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India has also agreed that a global deal should be reached at next year's climate conference and that greenhouse gas production should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
They also want to prevent food prices from rising and supported the convening of an international meeting to review the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister is going to the French capital today, where he is about to make a deal on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at the bilateral meeting.
In Paris, they hope that French companies will be commissioned to build Indian nuclear reactors worth EUR 20 billion.
According to news agencies, the agreement would be for 15 years.
More than 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Italian publishers are represented at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishing houses will be present at the most important international copyright meeting, the 60th Buchmesse fair.
At this year’s Frankfurt International Book Fair, 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries are expected, covering 171,790 square meters of floor space, where more than 403,000 books will be presented.
At the opening ceremony of the Italian Pavilion, the Italian Government will be represented by Francesco Maria Giro, Deputy State Secretary of the Ministry of Cultural Goods and Activities: Italy will occupy an exhibition area of 264 square metres through the establishment of a single Italia Point.
The opening ceremony will be followed by a press conference in the "Room Struktur" room of Buchmesse's 5.0 pavilion, which will also provide an opportunity to present data, trends and prospects on the state of play of Italian publishing.
According to the data, the proportion of foreign authors on the Italian publishing market is constantly decreasing, especially in the field of adult and youth publications.
Billionaire Steve Fossett's plane found missing a year ago
They found the remains of the billionaire Steve Fossett's plane, who disappeared over the Nevada desert on September 3rd, 2007.
The wreckage was found on a 3,000-metre high plateau in the vicinity of Mammoth Lakes, Sierra Nevada, on the border between California and Nevada.
No human remains were found inside the plane.
John Anderson, the sheriff of Madera County, dispelled all remaining doubts: "After determining the position of the plane, we sent out a team, and now we can be sure that it is the plane on which Steve Fossett flew the day he disappeared," he said in a press conference.
The sheriff also confirmed that no human remains were found in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Agency (NTSB) said that a few hours after the wreckage was discovered, a committee of inquiry was asked to identify the plane and determine that it was indeed the Bellanca 8kcab that disappeared on September 3, 2007, the day Fossett left Yerington, Nevada on a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, a couple found some of Fossett's personal belongings near his home in Mammoth Lakes.
Two IDs in the name of Fosset, issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, some cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was posted a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire has set up a number of peaks by which he has written himself into history.
In 2002, for the sixth time, he managed to fly around the world with a balloon for the first time: two weeks of lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the ground without landing.
Among his many records is the flight over the Andes, at a height of 15,445 meters, carried out by a copilot.
GLK, shocking advertising
An unusual, yet original and definite form of hobbyist with large surfaces and clean corners.
In a few words, this is Mercedes-Benz's latest compact SUV, with which the German car company tried to bring fresh momentum to the market.
It is precisely because of this unconventional content that the SUV GLK launch campaign, which will be available in Mercedes-Benz showrooms from 17 October, will also be surprising and unusual.
The advertising campaign accompanying the introduction of the new vehicle uses an unknown media communication tool, including utopian 3D posters that have not yet been used in Italy by a car brand.
The billboard action, which consists of three stages, will dominate Milan’s central shopping street, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of media communication will begin with a spatial presentation of the car, which will be visible in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional form with the help of special glasses distributed around the new SUV, Corso Como.
The viewer will feel as if the car is emerging from the poster.
Then, with the innovative Elumina8 technology, every detail of the new GLK becomes visible one by one, to form a unified image.
There is no doubt that Mercedes is trying to introduce something new into the stereotypical advertising world of the automotive industry with this promotion.
Is it possible to attract the attention of prospective buyers? We’ll see.
